<subSubSection id="C30A656ACF04FFBEFF25FEA274AFFDB6" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="8BAF36E1CF04FFBEFF25FEA2729CFE6E" blockId="11.[151,817,333,394]" box="[151,730,368,394]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<treatmentCitationGroup id="AB0011CFCF04FFBEFF25FEA2729CFE6E" box="[151,730,368,394]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<taxonomicName id="4C104D62CF04FFBEFF25FEA2720EFE6E" authority="Xu &amp; Li, 2007: 499" authorityName="Xu &amp; Li" authorityPageNumber="499" authorityYear="2007" box="[151,584,368,394]" class="Arachnida" family="Pimoidae" genus="Weintrauboa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="megacanthus">
<emphasis id="B964EAF3CF04FFBEFF25FEA27113FE6D" box="[151,341,368,393]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">W. megacanthus</emphasis>
<treatmentCitation id="0AB110F0CF04FFBEFEEFFEA2720EFE6E" author="Xu" box="[349,584,368,394]" page="499" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" year="2007">
<bibRefCitation id="EF814B10CF04FFBEFEEFFEA27248FE6E" author="Xu" box="[349,526,368,394]" pageId="11" pageNumber="18" refString="Xu, X. &amp; Li, S. Q. (2007) Taxonomic study of the spider family Pimoidae (Arachnida: Araneae) from China. Zoological Studies, 46, 483 - 502." type="journal article" year="2007">
Xu &amp; Li, 
<number id="3DD824C6CF04FFBEFE7DFEA27248FE6E" box="[463,526,368,394]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="2007.0">2007</number>
</bibRefCitation>
: 
<number id="3DD824C6CF04FFBEFDABFEA2720EFE6E" box="[537,584,368,394]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="499.0">499</number>
</treatmentCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, figs. 
<number id="3DD824C6CF04FFBEFD3CFEA27290FE6E" box="[654,726,368,394]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="78.0" valueMax="81.0" valueMin="75.0">75-81</number>
.
</treatmentCitationGroup>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BAF36E1CF04FFBEFF25FE1274AFFDB6" blockId="11.[151,1437,448,834]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
This species was recently described and illustrated, based on a single male specimen from the Sichuan Province (
<typeStatus id="54AB8843CF04FFBEFF68FE3A7148FDE6" box="[218,270,488,514]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">type</typeStatus>
specimen deposited at Institute of Zoology of the Chinese Academy of Sciences in Beijing; not examined). 
<taxonomicName id="4C104D62CF04FFBEFE91FDC27249FDCD" box="[291,527,528,553]" class="Arachnida" family="Pimoidae" genus="Putaoa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="megacantha">
<emphasis id="B964EAF3CF04FFBEFE91FDC27249FDCD" box="[291,527,528,553]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Putaoa megacantha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is hypothesized to be sister to 
<taxonomicName id="4C104D62CF04FFBEFC31FDC27447FDCD" box="[899,1025,528,553]" class="Arachnida" family="Pimoidae" genus="Putaoa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="huaping">
<emphasis id="B964EAF3CF04FFBEFC31FDC27447FDCD" box="[899,1025,528,553]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">P. huaping</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The female remains unknown. In this paper we provide a revised diagnosis in light of the description of 
<taxonomicName id="4C104D62CF04FFBEFC63FDEA740BFDB5" box="[977,1101,568,593]" class="Arachnida" family="Pimoidae" genus="Putaoa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="huaping" status="new species">
<emphasis id="B964EAF3CF04FFBEFC63FDEA740BFDB5" box="[977,1101,568,593]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">P. huaping</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2575788CF04FFBEFBE7FDEA74A3FDB6" box="[1109,1253,568,594]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30A656ACF04FFBEFF74FD8D7323FCA6" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BAF36E1CF04FFBEFF74FD8D7323FCA6" blockId="11.[151,1437,448,834]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis id="B964EAF3CF04FFBEFF74FD8D7100FD9D" bold="true" box="[198,326,607,633]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Males of 
<taxonomicName id="4C104D62CF04FFBEFE09FDB27220FD9D" box="[443,614,608,633]" class="Arachnida" family="Pimoidae" genus="Putaoa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="megacantha">
<emphasis id="B964EAF3CF04FFBEFE09FDB27220FD9D" box="[443,614,608,633]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">P. megacantha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from other pimoids by the large and conspicuous macroseta at the base of the ectal cymbial margin (
<bibRefCitation id="EF814B10CF04FFBEFD5DFD5A74C2FD46" author="Xu" box="[751,1156,648,674]" pageId="11" pageNumber="18" refString="Xu, X. &amp; Li, S. Q. (2007) Taxonomic study of the spider family Pimoidae (Arachnida: Araneae) from China. Zoological Studies, 46, 483 - 502." type="journal article" year="2007">
Xu &amp; Li 
<number id="3DD824C6CF04FFBEFCECFD5A73DBFD46" box="[862,925,648,674]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="2007.0">2007</number>
: figs. 
<number id="3DD824C6CF04FFBEFC56FD5A7447FD46" box="[996,1025,648,674]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="78.0">78</number>
and 
<number id="3DD824C6CF04FFBEFB8EFD5A74C2FD46" box="[1084,1156,648,674]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="80.5" valueMax="81.0" valueMin="80.0">80-81</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Both the embolus and the PEP are very different from those in 
<taxonomicName id="4C104D62CF04FFBEFDC7FD6272B5FD2D" box="[629,755,688,713]" class="Arachnida" family="Pimoidae" genus="Putaoa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="huaping" status="new species">
<emphasis id="B964EAF3CF04FFBEFDC7FD6272B5FD2D" box="[629,755,688,713]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">P. huaping</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2575788CF04FFBEFD48FD6273C1FD2E" box="[762,903,688,714]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
(compare 
<bibRefCitation id="EF814B10CF04FFBEFBB4FD6274F7FD2E" author="Xu" box="[1030,1201,688,714]" pageId="11" pageNumber="18" refString="Xu, X. &amp; Li, S. Q. (2007) Taxonomic study of the spider family Pimoidae (Arachnida: Araneae) from China. Zoological Studies, 46, 483 - 502." type="journal article" year="2007">
Xu &amp; Li 
<number id="3DD824C6CF04FFBEFBC0FD6274F7FD2E" box="[1138,1201,688,714]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="2007.0">2007</number>
</bibRefCitation>
: figs. 
<number id="3DD824C6CF04FFBEFB4AFD62757AFD2E" box="[1272,1340,688,714]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="80.0" valueMax="81.0" valueMin="79.0">79-81</number>
to 
<figureCitation id="132B2A64CF04FFBEFAD0FD6270E2FD16" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="7.[151,255,1916,1940]" captionTargetBox="[182,1410,215,1843]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[162,1447,194,1878]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 3. Putaoa huaping new species. Male pedipalp. A, ectal; B, ventral; C, dorsomesal (arrows point out to apical ends of pimoid embolic process). Scale bar, 0.2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/182551/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Figs. 
<number id="3DD824C6CF04FFBEFF25FD0A70E2FD16" box="[151,164,728,754]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
A-C). In 
<taxonomicName id="4C104D62CF04FFBEFEA2FD0A71FDFD15" box="[272,443,728,753]" class="Arachnida" family="Pimoidae" genus="Putaoa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="megacantha">
<emphasis id="B964EAF3CF04FFBEFEA2FD0A71FDFD15" box="[272,443,728,753]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">P. megacantha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the embolus is rather broad and forms a right angle with its base while in 
<taxonomicName id="4C104D62CF04FFBEFAADFD0A75DAFD15" box="[1311,1436,728,753]" class="Arachnida" family="Pimoidae" genus="Putaoa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="huaping">
<emphasis id="B964EAF3CF04FFBEFAADFD0A75DAFD15" box="[1311,1436,728,753]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">P. huaping</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the embolus is shorter and has a broad base. In 
<taxonomicName id="4C104D62CF04FFBEFD75FCD27332FCFD" box="[711,884,768,793]" class="Arachnida" family="Pimoidae" genus="Putaoa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="megacantha">
<emphasis id="B964EAF3CF04FFBEFD75FCD27332FCFD" box="[711,884,768,793]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">P. megacantha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the PEP is rather broad and forms a deep concavity while in 
<taxonomicName id="4C104D62CF04FFBEFEFEFCFA718FFCA5" box="[332,457,808,833]" class="Arachnida" family="Pimoidae" genus="Putaoa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="huaping">
<emphasis id="B964EAF3CF04FFBEFEFEFCFA718FFCA5" box="[332,457,808,833]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">P. huaping</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is highly bifurcated and pointed.
</paragraph>
